{"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "All three selectors find the element. The issue is NOT the selector - it's the timing. The page scrollHeight is 4535 now (after waiting 4s + scroll). When the test runs `window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)` early, the scrollHeight might still be small.\n\nKey insight: The element is in the DOM and visible AFTER the page fully loads (scrollHeight = 4535 after 4s wait). But the test's retry logic scrolls to `document.body.scrollHeight` without giving Builder.io time to expand the page.\n\nThe newsletter section is at y=3640 and the page is 4535px tall. The IntersectionObserver for Builder.io needs the user to scroll NEAR that section for it to render. But if we jump straight to scrollHeight = 285 (early load state), we never get near y=3640.\n\nActually wait - looking again: `byBgPrimary: FOUND` means `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` DOES exist in the DOM. And `visible: true` was shown earlier. Playwright's `waitFor({ state: 'visible' })` should find it.\n\nBut the test says it times out. This is puzzling. Let me think about what \"visible\" means in Playwright:\n- Playwright checks: element has non-zero size AND `display !== none` AND `visibility !== hidden` AND `opacity !== 0`\n- It does NOT require the element to be in the viewport\n\nSo if the element is in the DOM with visible=true, Playwright's waitFor should succeed. Unless...\n\nUnless Builder.io renders the section differently on CI/headless vs our current browser session. The MCP playwright browser might be running in headed mode, while the test runner (chromium, edge) might be running headless or with different viewport.\n\nOn headless/different viewport, Builder.io's IntersectionObserver might not trigger the newsletter section render because:\n1. The viewport is small and the section is far below\n2. IntersectionObserver only triggers when the element is actually in the viewport\n3. The newsletter section starts as a placeholder/empty div and only hydrates when scrolled into view\n\nThis means when the test runs headless:\n1. Page loads with placeholder sections\n2. `window.scrollTo(0, 285)` - scrolled to the bottom of the initial minimal page\n3. networkidle fires\n4. But the newsletter section placeholder was never visible in the viewport, so Builder.io never fetched/rendered the email input\n5. So `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` does NOT exist in the DOM\n\nOur MCP check showed it exists because our browser session had the page open for longer with user interaction.\n\nFix: The scroll strategy needs to be incremental - scroll down in steps of viewport height to trigger each IntersectionObserver as it comes into view.\n\nBetter approach: Use `page.evaluate` to scroll in increments, waiting between each step.\n\nActually the simplest robust fix: Instead of the current retry loop, replace with `page.evaluate(() => { ... incremental scroll ... })` that scrolls from top to bottom in steps.\n\nOR even better: Check if the element is in DOM, if not, do incremental scrolling.\n\nFor the test code in `home-page.spec.ts`, line 448:\n```\nawait page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n```\n\nChange to incremental scroll: scroll in steps of 500px waiting between each.\n\nBut changing the test seems risky. Let me think of a different approach.\n\nActually the cleanest fix is:\n1. In the scroll loop, instead of jumping to scrollHeight, scroll in viewport-sized increments\n2. This ensures each Builder.io section's IntersectionObserver fires as the viewport passes over it\n\nLet me look at the actual test retry loop more carefully:\n\n```javascript\nfor (let scrollAttempt = 0; scrollAttempt < 15; scrollAttempt++) {\n    const inputVisible = await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.isVisible().catch(() => false);\n    if (inputVisible) break;\n    await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n    await page.waitForTimeout(1_000);\n}\nawait homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 45_000 });\n```\n\nThe problem: Each iteration scrolls to `document.body.scrollHeight`, but if Builder.io hasn't rendered the newsletter section yet, scrollHeight is small and we're not triggering the IntersectionObserver for sections deep in the page.\n\nFix: Change the scroll strategy to incrementally scroll down:\n```javascript\n// Scroll down in viewport-sized steps to trigger all IntersectionObservers\nconst viewportHeight = page.viewportSize()?.height ?? 800;\nlet scrollPos = 0;\nfor (let scrollAttempt = 0; scrollAttempt < 20; scrollAttempt++) {\n    const inputVisible = await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.isVisible().catch(() => false);\n    if (inputVisible) break;\n    scrollPos += viewportHeight;\n    await page.evaluate((pos) => window.scrollTo(0, pos), scrollPos);\n    await page.waitForTimeout(800);\n    // If we've scrolled past the current page height, jump back and try again\n    const currentHeight = await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight);\n    if (scrollPos > currentHeight) {\n        scrollPos = 0;\n        await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, 0));\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually even simpler: just use `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded` on the locator WITHIN the retry loop (not just once before it). The current code calls it once BEFORE the loop and catches errors. If we call it INSIDE the loop with `force: true`, Playwright will scroll the element into view if it exists.\n\nAlternatively: the most reliable fix is to use `page.evaluate` with an incremental scroll inside the loop.\n\nLet me now check the PDP for the \"Set your store\" link issue.\n"}}
